summary: Announced legislation to maintain SBA loan programs and the SBIC program during a government shutdown to ensure small businesses retain access to capital, avoid operational disruptions, and preserve jobs; emphasized small businesses as the backbone of the economy and the need to protect employment and local economic stability during political standoffs. Also introduced the SBIR Website Improvement Act to make it easier for small businesses to find research partners and Phase III commercialization opportunities by improving SBIR/STTR award data and search functions, promoting partnerships that help translate R&D into marketable products and support job growth. Introduced the Expanding Child Care Access Act to provide start-up tax credits for family child care providers to expand local child care supply, reduce the childcare-related workforce exit of parents (disproportionately women and women of color), and help more parents remain employed. Additionally secured over $12.7 million in community project funding for transportation, water infrastructure, stormwater and environmental upgrades, public-safety facility upgrades, parks and recreation, community centers, libraries, and a hospital lab enhancement—investments presented as supporting local construction and maintenance jobs and broader economic activity in the district. His appointment to the House Small Business Committee was announced as a means to bring the voices of the district's roughly 13,000 small businesses to bear on policies affecting access to capital, entrepreneurship, and local economic development. The new senior staff slate includes personnel with labor and economic development backgrounds (Laney O’Shea's labor portfolio and Seth Levin's experience with the NJ AFL-CIO and economic development roles), strengthening the office's capacity to pursue job and labor priorities. Urged a prompt court ruling in the Gateway Development Commission lawsuit to release federal grant and loan funds for the Hudson Tunnel Project, warning that prolonged uncertainty threatens jobs and local economic activity for millions of commuters, workers, and businesses across the Northeast Corridor. Upon being sworn in, he committed to working to "uplift our economy" and to help working families in his district thrive, reaffirming a focus on job creation and economic opportunity for constituents.

Gill has highlighted private-sector investments tied to the Trump economic agenda as evidence of job creation and economic growth for Texans. In April 2025 he cited Abbott Laboratories' $500 million investment in Illinois and Texas, Paris Baguette's $160 million manufacturing plant in Texas, and LGM Pharma's $6 million expansion in Rosenberg, Texas, framing these announcements as delivering jobs and investment to his district under America First policies. In September 2025 he introduced the Domestic Jobs Protection Act, arguing that discretionary work permits create a 'magnet' for cheap labor that depresses wages and harms job prospects for working-class Americans and students; he frames the bill as protecting American workers' wages and employment opportunities by closing the executive-branch loophole that issues Employment Authorization Documents to unauthorized immigrants. In June 2025 he introduced the New IDEA Act to 'put American workers first' by eliminating financial incentives for employers to hire unauthorized workers, promoting robust and permanent E-Verify use, allowing job offers to be contingent on final verification, and using IRS data-sharing to detect and remove unauthorized workers—framing the legislation as protecting U.S. jobs and ensuring employers hire law-abiding Americans.

Supports workers' rights including the right to organize and collectively bargain for fair wages and safe working conditions. Has championed investments in apprenticeship and workforce training programs and led local efforts to protect workers' health and safety (for example, a countywide heat safety ordinance). Cosponsored bills to raise the minimum wage, strengthen pay equity (Raise the Wage Act, Paycheck Fairness Act), protect organizing rights, expand worker protections, and support workforce development in clean energy and other sectors. Upon being sworn in she pledged to sign a discharge petition for the Protect America's Workforce Act, signaling immediate support for congressional action to protect workers and labor standards.

Supports policies to expand career opportunities and compensation for professional boxers through H.R.4624, including establishing a national minimum payment per round and provisions intended to reduce exploitation of debut fighters and encourage investment in the sport. Also emphasizes the importance of major employers such as Delta Air Lines to job creation in his district—representing the most Delta employees of any Congressional District—and highlighted Delta's role in supporting tens of thousands of jobs and driving local economic activity. Recently led bipartisan passage of H.J. Res. 20 using the Congressional Review Act to repeal a Biden-era regulation that threatened production at Rinnai America's Griffin, GA manufacturing facility; that action was publicly credited with preserving over 200 jobs at the two-year-old Griffin plant, and he welcomed Secretary of Energy Chris Wright to the plant to celebrate the repeal, tour the assembly line, and meet workers. Promotes career and technical education as a workforce pipeline (toured CTE labs, convened roundtable with the Secretary of Education) to prepare students for precision manufacturing, healthcare, aviation, audio production, and other local in-demand jobs. Press materials also highlight repeated Cabinet visits (including the Secretary of Energy and Secretary of Housing and Urban Development) used to promote H.R.1 at a local factory, celebrate legislative wins that saved local jobs, and spotlight small business outreach. Most recently worked with the White House and Cabinet officials to pursue relief for a Biden-era refrigeration regulation that he says threatened 150 jobs at ALTA Refrigeration in Peachtree City, framing deregulation as essential to preserving local manufacturing employment. Additionally convened a bipartisan subcommittee hearing titled 'Beyond the Ballpark' to examine the economic impact of Minor League Baseball, featuring the Columbus Clingstones and witnesses including team owners and a small business owner, emphasizing the jobs and small-business activity generated by sports teams and related local economic activity. The Muhammad Ali American Boxing Revival Act emphasizes growing the number of professional boxing events held in the United States, which he argues will create event operations, hospitality, security, and venue jobs and boost revenues for nearby restaurants, hotels, and small businesses while setting a national minimum pay-per-round ($150) to raise fighter compensation. The December 2025 press release announcing Mike Tyson's endorsement underscored the bill's role in expanding opportunities for fighters and reviving the sport, reinforcing the economic and employment benefits tied to increased U.S.-based boxing events.
